<HEADLINE>
<P>
CITIES OFFERING BARGAIN PRICES TO AUTO DEALERS; 
</P>
<P>
TAXES: CAR DEALERSHIPS GENERATE SUBSTANTIAL SALES TAX REVENUES. AND SOME SAN 
GABRIEL VALLEY CITIES ARE CUTTING DEALS TO FILL THEIR NEW AUTO MALLS. 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By SIOK-HIAN TAY KELLEY, TIMES STAFF WRITER 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Like a star high school quarterback among throngs of hungry college recruiters, 
the auto dealer has become the darling of many revenue-hungry San Gabriel 
Valley city officials in the last decade. 
</P>
<P>
And in recent months, the mall skirmishes have become mall wars, as some 
officials offer increasingly sweet deals to lure dealers -- and their precious 
sales taxes -- to their respective cities, and others scramble to keep their 
established dealerships. 
</P>
<P>
"(Auto dealers) generate more sales tax per square foot of land than any other 
business a city can attract," explains Rob Steel, redevelopment director in 
Azusa. "That's why cities are fighting each other for them." 
</P>
<P>
But the zeal to retain and attract dealerships has sparked debate about the use 
of public funds to boost private enterprise, as well as exacting an emotional 
and financial cost to businessmen and homeowners who lie in the path of 
redevelopment and eminent domain. And some critics suggest that dealers are 
playing on cities' fears in order to win better deals. 
</P>
<P>
Nonetheless, city officials forge on. Three new auto dealers will begin 
construction at the Glendora Auto Center along the Foothill Freeway this month, 
breaking ground on a 32-acre complex that will become the newest car-shopper's 
paradise in the San Gabriel Valley. 
</P>
<P>
Eight dealerships will buy the land from the redevelopment agency for 
essentially 50% of its value. In return, the city gets at least $1 million a 
year in expected new tax revenue once the mall is completed. 
</P>
<P>
The city manager called the project one of the council's most important and 
positive moves in the city's history. But critics have blasted it as a 
"sweetheart deal" that is setting back the city $13 million. 
</P>
<P>
Pomona is offering land valued at $6 per square foot for between $1.50 and 
$2.50 per square foot at a 57-acre auto center to be built north of the Pomona 
Freeway. Monrovia and Duarte had been selling land for their adjoining 
18-dealer, 47-acre 210 Freeway Autoplex, scheduled for completion next year, 
from as low as $7 per square foot. 
</P>
<P>
In Pasadena, where six dealers have left the city in the last two years, the 
average cost of commercial land is $30 a square foot. Desperate to keep its 
remaining 16 dealerships from deserting, Pasadena is considering offering 
dealers rebates of up to 50% of the sales tax that would be due to the city 
should the dealers decide to build or expand. 
</P>
<P>
Alhambra -- whose 20 auto dealers are projected to generate $2.1 million in 
sales tax in the 1989-90 fiscal year -- has helped dealers on leased land 
purchase sites so they don't have to deal with skyrocketing real estate costs. 
And last month, Covina, which has lost two dealerships to a mall in neighboring 
West Covina, condemned a retail center to acquire land for up to two new 
dealerships. 
</P>
<P>
"They won't pay more than $5 per square foot for land valued at $10 to $20 per 
square foot, and cities are happy to offer them that," Covina Planner Hal 
Ledford said. 
</P>
<P>
Leonard Eliot, assistant exececutive director of West Covina's redevelopment 
agency, said the dealerships are attractive because they are "large ticket 
items." 
</P>
<P>
"Cities are generally looking for revenue, and sales tax is one item we have 
the greatest amount of control over," he said. 
</P>
<P>
City officials say that since the passage of Proposition 13 in 1978, cities 
have been forced to turn to sales taxes rather than property taxes as a steady 
source of general fund revenue. The landmark measure slashed property taxes to 
1% of a parcel's value and restricted increases in assessments to 2% annually. 
</P>
<P>
Ever since the success of the Cerritos Auto Center -- which opened in 1980 and 
was one of the first in the Los Angeles area -- the malls have tempted city 
officials, said Mike Martin, redevelopment director of Alhambra. 
</P>
<P>
"It also showed the impact on surrounding cities like Downey and South Gate," 
which had to fight to retain their dealers, he said. "That's a real sobering 
thought. The cities that have been able to respond will come out on top." 
</P>
<P>
Alhambra City Manager Kevin Murphy said several dealers in the city "came to us 
in '84, '85 planning to move out of town unless we helped them." The city 
decided then to develop an 18-dealership mall along Main Street. The project 
should be 90% complete within two years, Martin said. 
</P>
<P>
Although most officials maintain that competition for dealers is friendly, they 
admit they hate to see one leave. 
</P>
<P>
"Conflict has arisen when a city successfully gets an auto franchise from an 
adjoining city," Eliot said. "That has caused some bad feeling between some 
cities sometimes." 
</P>
<P>
But certain officials say they think cities are letting dealers take advantage 
of them. 
</P>
<P>
Glendora Councilman David Bodley, who voted against the Glendora mall last 
November, charged that dealers are exploiting cities by shopping around for the 
best deals. 
</P>
<P>
"They're very good businessmen, and they are using all of the fears of all of 
the cities about revenue, or the lack of it, to get the best deal," he said. 
</P>
<P>
"As dealerships become more sophisticated in realizing how great an asset they 
are to cities, they begin playing cities off against each other," said West 
Covina's Eliot. 
</P>
<P>
"One dealer (approached by Glendora) wants us to buy property for them to 
expand," he said. "We're looking into it." 
</P>
<P>
Warren Person, a West Covina Oldsmobile dealer who is asking the city to help 
him acquire 40,000 square feet for expansion, said he has to do what is in the 
best interest for his company. 
</P>
<P>
"I'm in a redevelopment district, and obviously they don't want me to move to 
Glendora," he said, adding that he would prefer to remain loyal to West Covina. 
</P>
<P>
Chester Yoshizaki, West Covina's redevelopment manager, said the whole point of 
his agency was to help existing businesses. 
</P>
<P>
"We automatically respond any way we can," Yoshizaki said. "Everything we can 
do to keep them here would be to our benefit." 
</P>
<P>
West Covina collected $1.7 million in sales tax from auto dealers in 1988-89. 
Of the city's 12 dealerships, nine are in the 18-acre West Covina Auto Plaza 
along the San Bernardino Freeway completed in 1986. 
</P>
<P>
Some city officials complain that dealers will sometimes use the threat of 
leaving as a bargaining chip to get concessions from redevelopment agencies. 
</P>
<P>
"These guys are car salesmen; they can negotiate," said Martin, referring to 
Alhambra dealers who "will hint to make you understand there is cheaper land 
elsewhere in the world." 
</P>
<P>
Ledford said this encourages cities to "steal businesses from one another. It 
results in cities competing and giving money to businesses, instead of services 
to people." 
</P>
<P>
Eliot warned: "It's estructive for cities to upbid each other. It's going to 
cost them more and more." 
</P>
<P>
Because the creation of almost every mall is organized by a redevelopment 
agency, another complaint arises when the power of eminent domain is sometimes 
exercised in assembling land. 
</P>
<P>
"You can't put a price tag on people," said Sherry Passmore, a slow-growth 
advocate who has served as a consultant to residents fighting condemnation. "It 
adds insult to injury when you find it's for a businessman." 
</P>
<P>
Christina Lizardo, whose 9,000-square-foot lot was taken by eminent domain for 
the mall in Duarte, took the case to court and finally settled with the city in 
July. 
</P>
<P>
"It was very stressful trying to find a house when I hadn't planned to sell in 
the first place," she said. "If the school or freeway was expanding and they 
had to take homes, it would have been a lot easier for us to swallow." 
</P>
<P>
No homes were taken for the Glendora center, but a slow-growth group, Glendora 
Pride, objected to the project. "We're opposed to the use of public funds for 
private enterprise," said association president Judy Lawford. 
</P>
<P>
Darlene Avina, a past president of the group, called the arrangement with the 
dealers a "sweetheart deal." She pointed out that the redevelopment agency has 
already helped one of the dealers acquire his existing site. 
</P>
<P>
Glendora Finance Director Larry Shroeder said Fred and Carl Colley, who jointly 
own Ford, Volkswagen and Subaru dealerships in the city, owe the redevelopment 
agency $2.8 million for land the agency purchased for them in 1983. They have 
until 2008 to repay the debt. 
</P>
<P>
The Colleys already have "a low-interest loan from us, and now (they're) coming 
back and getting more. Why is the city helping them get rich?" 
</P>
<P>
Dealers contend that finding a good location is a matter of survival and that 
land prices make help from cities almost essential. 
</P>
<P>
"Dealers that don't get onto freeway locations will find it very difficult to 
survive," said Carl Colley, who was negotiating to move to San Dimas when 
Glendora approved its mall. The Colleys will relocate to the freeway mall next 
year. 
</P>
<P>
Pasadena Motorcar Dealers Assn. president Charles Pachdjian , will be moving 
his Oldsmobile dealership to the Monrovia mall next summer. 
</P>
<P>
"As these malls go in, it's got to hurt dealers in towns like Pasadena that 
don't have one," he said. "Every dealer in this town would move out" if there 
weren't similar franchises already at the malls, he said. He hopes the freeway 
exposure will increase his annual sales from $15 million to $20 million. 
</P>
<P>
Duarte, which expects $2 million to $3 million in additional sales taxes from 
the 10 dealerships on its share of the mall, expects to recoup the $7.5 million 
it spent to create the package within 14 years. 
</P>
<P>
"The key is to be conservative on sales tax projections. That will help even 
out those peaks and valleys in the industry," said City Manager Jesse Duff. But 
no matter how careful the analysis and planning, he said, "you always have a 
concern about giving away too much." 
</P>
<P>
HOW CITIES LURE AUTO DEALERS 
</P>
<P>
Alhambra Helped existing Main Street dealers upgrade and relocated others to 
that street to create an 18-dealership strip. Also helped dealers purchase land 
so they wouldn't have to continue leasing. 
</P>
<P>
Claremont;Assembled and sold land with no discount for a seven-dealership auto 
park that opened in 1986. 
</P>
<P>
Covina;Condemned retail center last month to create space for up to two new 
auto dealerships on Citrus Avenue and intends to help two other dealers upgrade 
and expand. 
</P>
<P>
Glendora;Looking for dealers to fill two remaining slots in its 
eight-dealership mall along Foothill Freeway. The city is asking for about 50% 
of the land value as down payment. The remainder will be forgiven if the dealer 
generates the equivalent in sales tax over the next 10 years. Groundbreaking 
for the first three dealerships began this month. 
</P>
<P>
Monrovia-Duarte;Sold dealers land for $6 to $15 per square foot, depending on 
when dealers signed up for a space at their 18-dealership 210 Freeway Autoplex, 
to be completed in 1990. 
</P>
<P>
Pasadena;Considering sales tax rebate to dealers who want to build or expand. 
</P>
<P>
Pomona;Asking for $1.50 to $2.50 per square foot for spaces in a 
nine-dealership mall along the Pomona Freeway. Three dealers have already 
agreed to move in. 
</P>
<P>
West Covina;Opened a nine-dealership mall along the San Bernardino Freeway in 
1986 and is considering helping a dealer outside the mall expand. 
</P>
</TEXT>
<GRAPHIC>
<P>
Photo, Auto dealerships like these on Mountain Avenue in Monrovia generate 
substantial sales tax revenues for cities. MARC MARTIN / Los Angeles Times 
</P>
</GRAPHIC>
