<HEADLINE>
<P>
WATER AND GROWTH 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Kudos goes to staff writer Bill Billiter for his perceptive articles expressing 
the "essence" of South County's water problems. 
</P>
<P>
Ah, yes! The initial water crisis was over by September for San Clemente and 
the other customers of the Tri-Cities district; however, the water shortage 
problems were not. 
</P>
<P>
Billiter's articles stressed the need not only for emergency conservation 
measures but also for a permanent allocation plan -- a plan urged and 
supported. After all, four customers shared a single, finite water source. They 
will continue to share a single supply. Yet San Clemente, the largest and 
fastest-growing customer, has not recognized the need for the plan. 
</P>
<P>
Projected additional supplies are not guaranteed, and reclaimed water 
facilities won't release enough potable water to satisfy future demands, 
according to staff. Where does the city go from here? Councilman Tom Lorch 
wanted to know too, the only council member to express concern about the 
growth-water issue. More's the pity. 
</P>
<P>
KAROLINE KOESTER 
</P>
<P>
San Clemente 
</P>
</TEXT>
