<P>
Photo, Smoking Lamp Goes Out With Pomp and Big Puff There was a lot of smoke, 
but they put out the fire for good at the Veterans Administration Hospital in 
Long Beach. The occasion was a celebration at noon Thursday billed as "Kicking 
the Habutt." The kickoff centered around a giant, 20-foot-long cigarette that 
was cradled in an oversize 4-foot ashtray decked out with balloons in the 
hospital patio area. Archie Sanchez, left, of Paramount lights the symbolic 
cigarette he designed that looks the size of a cannon. Then team captains 
representing 40 quitters of the smoking habit run up with fire extinguishers to 
put out the cigarette, top left. Later, people who pledged to quit smoking were 
handed a survival guide and given a chance to autograph the cigarette before it 
was destroyed by a "Cigarette Buster" wielding a chain saw. Adding to the color 
of the occasion were uniformed cheerleaders from Monte Vista High School, a 
72-member marching band and special speakers. The veterans hospital declared 
itself a smoke-free environment beginning Monday to coincide with the Great 
American Smokeout day. The policy will apply to everyone -- employees, 
patients, volunteers and visitors to the medical center. Smoking cessation 
classes will be offered to assist people in kicking the habit. Officials said 
the policy is intended to set an example in the community for clean air and 
good health, and enhance the well-being of patients and employees. KAREN TAPIA 
/Los Angeles Times 
</P>
